There are several versions of how Thureos appeared in Greece. According to one, it was borrowed from the Eastern Celts who settled in the Danube Valley, who penetrated far to the east in 281 BC. e. to Thrace, whom the Greeks called the Galatians. However, the Thracian and Illyrian infantry began to use the thureos before the Greeks. According to another version, the Greeks adopted the thureos during the Pyrrhus campaign in Italy from the allies of the Oscans and / or their opponents of the Romans, who had a scutum that also had an umbon Thureophores were an intermediate link between skirmishers and phalangites, often replacing peltasts.